<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06122273 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06122273 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  RAILROAD; TRANSPORTATION; INCREASE; SERVICE; BEGIN; SOUTH; SAN-JOSE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Almost 12,000 people celebrated the extension of light-rail services intoSouth San Jose last week, jamming the park and ride lot of theOhlone/Chynoweth light-rail station and starting what transit officials hopewill be the beginning of a beautiful relationship.;    That number was almost4,000 more than hoped for, said Lili Smith, spokeswoman for the Santa ClaraCounty Transportation Agency.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  East Extra  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  SOUTH S.J. WELCOMES LIGHT-RAIL EXTENSION  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Also ran in EX4/1  </MEMO><TEXT>     &quot;It was a pleasant surprise to have so many people come out to greet lightrail,&quot; Smith said.;    It was an eager, upbeat crowd ready to hop aboard thevehicles they had seen shuttling around their neighborhoods for the pastmonth. The new extension of the railway system will link neighborhoods insouthern portion of the city with downtown San Jose and beyond.;    Linesstretched everywhere throughout the park-and-ride lot, which served as thesite for the kick-off celebration. There were giveaways galore, ranging fromfree french fries to paper models of light-rail cars. Even former SanFrancisco 49er Ronnie Lott was on hand signing autographs and promoting hisnew fitness club, which recently opened in the South San Jose area.;    &quot;We'rehere because we want to check out the new train,&quot; said Billy Raby, who broughtalong his video camera to record the event.;    If Thursday night's crowd wasany indication of how folks in the South Valley feel about the new extension,it could be good news for transit officials who are hoping the 10-mileaddition will boost ridership along the 20-mile corridor from its current11,000 to more than 20,000 passengers by summer.;    The opening of thelight-rail extension into the Almaden and Blossom Valley neighborhoodsrepresents the railway's second stretch into a residential area. The firstmove into the city's suburban areas came last August, when officials openedthe Tamien Station in the Willow Glen area. Ridership there has already almostdoubled, with residents venturing in from the west and east sides of the cityto commute by rail.;    The southern light-rail extension is the secondtransportation project to open in the South Valley in the past month. Athree-mile stretch of Highway 85, which, when complete, will move commutersfrom South San Jose to Sunnyvale and beyond, was christened in March, thoughrain delays pushed back its opening to April. The new light-rail segment runsthrough the median of Highway 85.;    Even before the first train opened itsdoors, Brenda Eden-Swede and Gil Cruz of New Looks Salon in downtown San Josewere already helping the crowd get into the spirit of things. The two tootedand beeped through the throngs of people outfitted as a light-rail car.;   &quot;Contrary to skeptics and cynics this is no white elephant. This light-railtrain will move people from their homes into the downtown area to workplaces,&quot;said Congressman Norman Mineta, who was one of several city, county and stateofficials who gathered for the celebration.;    Last week's celebrationculminated with a crescendo of music and a burst of color.;    Fidgetingchildren quieted down and ceased wiggling. Families ohhhed and awwwed as thesky over South San Jose erupted in a dazzling array of fireworks. Minuteslater, a light-rail vehicle appeared on the scene and folks were invited totake an inaugural ride.;    IF YOU'RE INTERESTED; Adult fares for the lightrail are 75 cents each way during commute hours -- from 6 to 9 a.m. and after3 p.m. The fare for children under 17 is 50 cents. The fare for older peopleand the disabled is 10 cents. Hours of operation are from 4:45 a.m. to 12:30a.m. Monday through Friday and 6 a.m. to 12:30 a.m. weekends and holidays.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  LORI ARATANI, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910501  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  May  </MONTH><PG.COL>  5  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  622  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday May 1, 199100122273,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>